Hello and welcome to 6 Minute English, I'm Neil.

4
00:00:15,040 --> 00:00:16,559
And hello, I'm Rob.

5
00:00:16,559 --> 00:00:19,920
In 6 Minute English, we often talk about food, don't we, Rob?

6
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:23,600
Oh yes, and I love food. It's a very important topic.

7
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:27,679
We know that too much of the wrong kind of food can be bad for our health,

8
00:00:27,679 --> 00:00:30,800
but there is another way that food can be harmful for some people.

9
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:34,479
Yes, you're right. Some people have food allergies.

10
00:00:34,479 --> 00:00:37,439
They can become very ill if they eat certain foods,

11
00:00:37,439 --> 00:00:40,719
such as peanuts, shellfish, milk and so on.

12
00:00:40,719 --> 00:00:42,640
So, Neil, do you have any food allergies?

13
00:00:42,640 --> 00:00:47,840
Fortunately, I don't, but my daughter is allergic to tree nuts.

14
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:50,399
And so she gets very ill if she eats those. No, dear.

15
00:00:50,399 --> 00:00:53,280
Well, it seems as if there are more food allergies these days,

16
00:00:53,280 --> 00:00:57,120
or more people have them. Or maybe it's just in the news more.

17
00:00:57,119 --> 00:01:01,599
Well, that's a very interesting point because that is the topic of this program.

18
00:01:01,599 --> 00:01:04,879
Before we find out more though, here is our question.

19
00:01:04,879 --> 00:01:08,640
One of the most common food allergies is to peanuts.

20
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:11,120
Now, what kind of food is a peanut?

21
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:16,400
Is it a vegetable, be a nut or see a legume?

22
00:01:16,400 --> 00:01:18,719
Oh, come on, a peanut is a nut.

23
00:01:18,719 --> 00:01:20,319
There's a clue in the name there, Neil.

24
00:01:20,959 --> 00:01:22,560
But that would be too easy, wouldn't it?

25
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:26,000
So, I'm going to say that I've got no idea what a legume is,

26
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:27,840
so that's my answer, see.

27
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:30,400
I'll have the answer at the end of the program.

28
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:34,719
To help answer the question as to whether food allergies are more common now,

29
00:01:34,719 --> 00:01:40,560
here's Dr Adam Fox, who is speaking on the food program on BBC Radio 4.

30
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:42,719
Does he think there has been an increase?

31
00:01:43,439 --> 00:01:46,719
I think we can be very confident if you look back over say 30 or 40 years,

32
00:01:46,719 --> 00:01:50,079
that there are much more allergic problems around now than there were.

33
00:01:50,079 --> 00:01:53,680
So, for example, very robust studies that look at prevalence of things like

34
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:59,120
eczema, food allergy, do show really significant increases over 20, 30 years, for example.

35
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:02,240
Has there been an increase?

36
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:06,400
Well, yes, he says there have been significant increases.

37
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:10,000
This means there has been a clear and obvious rise.

38
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:11,760
Why does he think that?

39
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:14,719
He said that there have been robust studies.

40
00:02:14,719 --> 00:02:18,400
A study is a piece of research, and if you say a study is robust,

41
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:23,280
it means that it was very detailed and conducted thoroughly to a high standard.

42
00:02:23,280 --> 00:02:27,120
He said that these studies looked at the prevalence of a few things.

43
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:31,840
Prevalence is a noun that refers to how common something is, how often it happens.

44
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:36,080
One of the things they looked at, as well as food allergies, was eczema.

45
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:39,680
This is a skin condition that usually happens in childhood.

46
00:02:39,680 --> 00:02:44,319
The skin can get red, itchy and painful over different parts of the body.

47
00:02:44,319 --> 00:02:46,000
Here's Dr Fox again.

48
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,199
I think we can be very confident if you look back over say 30 or 40 years,

49
00:02:49,199 --> 00:02:52,639
that there are much more allergic problems around now than there were.

50
00:02:52,719 --> 00:02:56,799
For example, very robust studies that look at prevalence of things like eczema,

51
00:02:56,799 --> 00:03:02,000
food allergy, do show really significant increases over 20, 30 years, for example.

52
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:05,279
So what is the reason for the increase in food allergies?

53
00:03:05,279 --> 00:03:06,559
Is it genetics?

54
00:03:06,559 --> 00:03:07,919
Dr Fox again.

55
00:03:07,919 --> 00:03:09,839
We certainly can't put it down to genetics,

56
00:03:09,839 --> 00:03:13,039
and we now understand that there is a key role for eczema.

57
00:03:13,039 --> 00:03:18,159
So there's a pretty direct relationship between whether you've got eczema during infancy

58
00:03:18,159 --> 00:03:20,000
and your likelihood of getting a food allergy.

59
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:21,520
Is it genetics?

60
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:25,919
No. He says you can't put it down to genetics,

61
00:03:25,919 --> 00:03:28,800
which means you can't explain it by genetics.

62
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:32,560
In fact, according to the research, if you have eczema as a child,

63
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:34,960
you are more likely to develop food allergies.

64
00:03:34,960 --> 00:03:37,199
Here's Dr Fox one more time.

65
00:03:37,199 --> 00:03:39,520
We certainly can't put it down to genetics,

66
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:42,400
and we now understand that there is a key role for eczema.

67
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:48,000
So there's a pretty direct relationship between whether you've got eczema during infancy

68
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:50,000
and your likelihood of getting a food allergy.

69
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:53,039
Okay, now time to review our vocabulary,

70
00:03:53,039 --> 00:03:56,879
